<iframe class="youtube" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/lxxndOskI1o" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>

<p>Open command line and navigate to your packageâ€™s folder</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>cmd
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Login your npm account</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>npm login
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Note that when you input the password, there is no clue show that you are typing. This will be confused if this is the first time you use the command line.</p>

<p>Initialize npm package manager</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>npm init
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If you have prepared your package, all you need to do is just enter.</p>

<p>Finally, type</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>yes
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>Publish your package</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>npm publish
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>If you see the line</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>+ your-pkg-name@1.0.1
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>your package has been published on npm successfully!</p>

<p>If there is any error, you should:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Check your packageâ€™s name, it maybe used by other user (for example: you canâ€™t name your package <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">react</code> or <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">vue</code>). In this case, you should change your packageâ€™s name, or publish your package under your name or organizationâ€™s name.</li>
  <li>Check your folderâ€™s structure, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">package.json</code> file.</li>
  <li>Check your npm account.</li>
</ul>
